The Prague Stock Exchange falls into minus by close of business.
After the steep fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions with the shares of ČEZ reached almost half of the normal day-to-day business.
At the beginning of Tuesday's business, the Prague Stock Exchange began to break down on Monday, when it fell by another six percentage points.
This time the reason for the burglary was Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the market's response to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which had refused to support a stabilisation plan for the financial sector there, is evident.
Case of shares in Asia
On Tuesday, stocks on the Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall, although the indices were able to offset some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng Stock Exchange index lost almost four percentage points over the course of the business day, but was later able to offset some of the losses, thus reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which observes the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, the markets were closed in Shanghai.
The shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but then reduced the losses to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange decreased by 3.6 percent according to the index there.
"The timing for the bailout in the US is uncertain and will affect financial markets worldwide," said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Hong Kong, although it belongs to China, determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, American legislators should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and pass the bill for financial support.
Otherwise, it would threaten that other countries would also be affected by the burglary.
A Bloodbath of American Stocks
On Monday, the American House of Representatives rejected the plan to support the financial system, for which up to $700 billion (almost Kč 12 trillion) should be spent.
The legislators thus ignored President George Bush's request to support the plan.
Bush's view that the plan would address the underlying causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilise the entire economy.
American stocks were going through a bloodbath on Monday, and the main stock indices recorded the biggest slump in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell by almost seven percent, a similar slump he had most recently recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there was hardly any indication that the draft would not get through in the House of Deputies, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress makes concession: US government allowed to pump $700 billion into banks
The top representatives of American Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement on financial assistance to the American financial system.
This will be voted on at the beginning of next week.
American legislators made a breakthrough in talks about the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of financial assistance to the American financial system to the tune of $700 billion (about $12 trillion).
However, this does not yet mean a victory.
In fact, Congressmen still need to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish and vote on the final version of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in American Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the Chairman of the Banking and Financial Services Committee, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
In the Senate, according to different data, it is likely that the plan could be voted on at the earliest on Wednesday.
According to economists, a communication on the adoption of the plan should be the first major psychological factor in stimulating financial markets.
After that, however, there would be a "disillusionment" due to the complicated mechanisms, as one could also help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a market stabilisation package should look like," said Democrat Nancy Pelosi to the agency Bloomberg.
According to her, a final vote could still be held on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislators met with American Secretary of State Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give the government fund its final form.
This provides for the purchase of unsaleable mortgage assets from financial companies, which plunge the financial firms into heavy losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We need to continue the recovery plan, but I think we're at the end of the process," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to the Democratic Senator of Nevada, Harry Reid, legislators are trying to reach a final agreement before Sunday in Congress.
The aim was to reassure investors of the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a decision by the Congress could influence the business on Monday.
So far, however, it is not quite clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, and there is also confusion as to whether the negotiations could still fail at the last minute due to a problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the next few days.
But the law will undergo some changes.
The total amount earmarked for assistance to the system will be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion will be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
But Congress can block the payout of the remaining money if it has the impression that the program does not perform its function, at a further $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush views progress in negotiations as positive
Although the president has a right of veto in this decision, Congress may overrule its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program has persisted, based on obtaining finance for the purchase of bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
"We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on Sunday on the law, the Senate then on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
American President Bush was also pleased with the progress.
His spokesman Tony Fratto stated that Bush was satisfied with Saturday's progress and "estimated the bilateral effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Limitation of golden parachutes
The Chairman of the Banking Committee of the Senate, Christopher Dodd, the senior negotiator, stated that the legislators had agreed on a responsibility for the money program, the protection of taxpayers against losses, the conclusion of benefits and a timetable for financing the plan.
The new law also aims to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies involved in the programme and sets up a committee to oversee the fund.
This is to be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on it and achieved a great advance towards an agreement that works and is important for the market and for all Americans," says Paulson.
The plan also expects help for homeowners who have problems with the repayment of their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new mortgage rates that it buys, with the aim of reducing the monthly costs for the debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to the chief economist of Patria Finance David Marek, but implementation will be very difficult.
"It is because one does not know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are bought up.
This will be crucial for how the financial sector and the government share the losses among each other," Marek said this week to the server iHNed.cz.
According to Marek, whether the plan will be adopted now or at the beginning of next week is not decisive.
"It is much more important that Congressmen agree to support the plan and say goodbye to it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement that it will be adopted is the most important thing at this moment," Marek stressed.
Duel on Messer's cutting edge: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls yet.
So, of course, it looks like it's better to buy just one phone.
Nevertheless, there are enough reasons why you should get an independent player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of the future owner.
Sure, it's hard to buy a great expensive record player at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
Once such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
However, if you have LPs with Art Rock, Jazz or Blues on your shelf, you probably dream of at least one of them.
This is also the case with music on travel, i.e. with compressed music, expressed in a simplified way - music in MP3 format.
Again, there are price and quality categories.
For one, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, but a Pink-Floyd fan will also be hard to take headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide-ranging.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some good music players can play much more than just music, but what mobile phones can do doesn't even make a hint.
No modern device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, calling and simsing, it can play music and videos, record both, it has a better camera, sometimes a worse camera and may also be able to navigate.
And if you still include the smartphones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a little miracle, because no fridge can grill and no TV can photograph.
But the universality of mobile phones also brings disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you will have to reload it.
And playing music is one of the greatest energy eaters.
Only a few mobile phones can play music for more than ten-twelve hours, usually much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest) are significantly more powerful.
That's why you should expect cheap phones to be able to play music for no longer than a few hours.
If you then call from time to time, you prefer to buy a charger for the office - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players you will not have this problem, even the less good will last at least 9 hours uninterrupted operation with one time charging out.
Another problem is if you want to play the music on your cell phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices have a USB connection, besides, not every mobile phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, the music can be transferred directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers can handle the tiny memory cards used in cell phones without reduction.
With players you do not need any special software except for exceptions (iPod).
You only need to feed the device via USB port with music from your PC.
Most mobile phones and players create a music library themselves, ordered by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the evaluation by users.
Some devices only represent the tree structure of the address directory, similar to Windows Explorer, some can both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can be more
