For three and four thousand crowns you already get a decent walkman.
The biggest handicap for most will be that there are no normal headphones.
The best and most technically sophisticated phones with a 3.5 mm opening for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players is the easy operation.
The simplest - and not necessarily cheapest (see selection) - players can really be used by everyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity when operating with the former normal cassette recorder or, for example, the record player is obvious.
There is no threat of a collision in the form of an erroneously employed mobile Internet and a subsequent horrendous invoice for data transmissions.
Which device should be used now
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g.Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable storage media (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns are sufficient.
But respect.
The basic models usually only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive can read 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, then grab Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to place more than 1100 crowns on the table.
Be among the more demanding listeners, prefer to take specialized mobile phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some of Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have stand-alone control buttons for MP3, and the ease of use comes to that of a single MP3 player.
The furthest is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman mobile phones have the same user interface as the individually sold MP3 players.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours) provide MP3 players from the above mentioned manufacturers.
The first virtual provider is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe he won't be waiting long.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of a text message is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the European Commission's final steps in regulating roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a battle announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that there is an extremely high level of competition on the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák often agrees with this, who had often said in the past that there was no place for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has much chance (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is one more possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought with it a significant price reduction, to which then also the classical mobile operators had to react.
Even before such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, there were similar voices to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, it doesn't take long to look for examples.
In February we reported about the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider succeeded in attracting more than 100 thousand customers, making it the fifth largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns, among other things, U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be able to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually stand out as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to focus on a non-clichetic target group.
This provider is specifically targeted at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and whom they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also gain a foothold in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone Miroslav Čepický's press officer also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of service provision."
In the Czech Republic, the mobile operators believe that there is no chance
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region," says Jana Studničková, spokesman of the Penta financial group, in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
Their interest in launching a virtual mobile provider has been shown for some time by the GTS Novera group, which wants to take a further step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the corporate clients sector.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already achieved progress in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, press officer.
Maybe better times are coming.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specificities over other markets.
No subject has yet addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sršeň from Telefónica O2's press department in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other suppliers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile press officer Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build on."
And she adds: "In the network of T-Mobile, hardly any virtual provider will appear by the end of the year.
At this moment, we should already have a concrete offer in order to be able to think in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický comments: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure sharing.
This is exactly what we consider the best from the customers' point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider means more competition, this would lead to lower prices and thus also to a decline in profits.
So why should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
The fact that providers can pull together when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ was at the time when U:fon came on the market from the company T-Mobile.
This is also demonstrated by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
Now, however, U:fon is a good argument as to why you shouldn't allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
However, given this approach of mobile operators, the absolute lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of ČTÚ, which unfortunately - unlike Great Britain and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
The latter holds only the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, applied to this whole problem its very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider via the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classical suppliers," said Kristián Chalupa of the External Relations Department of the ÚOHS in his reply to our request.
Such a formulation would not surprise representatives of suppliers.
This is more than worrying by an authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside the country, where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not part of the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, the almost touching harmony of the three mobile operators resulting from their reactions is really shocking.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same petrol price at the petrol stations is surely just coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs of anti-competitive action in this matter, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the suppliers have a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The regulatory authority for telecommunications is also likely to lack the necessary tools to open up the mobile market to virtual providers," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the approval of the network operator is always necessary for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And, logically, the mobile provider has a monopoly on its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if you do not go along with this argument, it should at least be a warning to the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The transfer of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a quite common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This was already observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, it has not been possible to introduce the extension of ČTÚ's competences to the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's all right when no one's looking
First of all, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
It is companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but are only partially public.
Usually they are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Our own mobile telephone services include Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar kind of resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, it may be a violation of the contractual terms that we will then deal with, which may lead to an end to the cooperation with the relevant company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
It is, however, quite unlikely that such a thing will not be heard by those in charge of the mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, there may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
In fact, these companies are not subject to negligible profits, but at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite all the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone doesn't run on their name, so they can't have it in full like the normal customers of mobile providers."
But the ČTÚ should at least seem strange.
A further question opens up for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an approach, why are they blocking a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competencies to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the statement of the providers that they do not know about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been stressed several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers resulted in a significant drop in the price of the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have been created, the classic providers have tried to prevent their creation more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market which was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, it was precisely at this moment that the regulatory bodies intervened, which did not seek to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Be it through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator emerged, and this was followed by more.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing up the whole case like a hot potato.
On the basis of our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in competences is more than favourable in these cases.
But let's not throw the shotgun in the corn.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon start moving again.
If a provider permits the emergence of a virtual mobile provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not make more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new photos of the national anthem Wo ist my home country on the occasion of the Day of Czech Statehood in a ceremony.
The anthem was re-recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo singing, in choir version and in an instrumental version.
The vocal version was taken over by Kateřina Knková and Adam Plachetka.
The editors of the hymn versions are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national song is one of the most beautiful hymns.
He had already told the Czech radio that he had chosen singers with young, representative voices for the solo variants, which are striking and popular.
"From the very beginning, I tried with both and then with the choir to adhere to a clear diction so that one can understand the text well, so that a harmony can be created," the conductor said.
The Czech national anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song "Kde domov můj" was first performed in 1834 on the stage of the Ständetheater in the originally Czech play "Fidlovačka" by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music was by František Škroup.
It became popular, and people spontaneously accepted it.
The first verse of the song then became an organic part of the national anthem after the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
