The Prague transport companies will also transport on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will enter the history of Prague's transport companies as a date when the first passengers who carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket will enter a subway, tram or bus.
They can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and play it on their chip card at the same time, in the information centers and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraşı Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons are also available on the Internet since yesterday on the website of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use Internet sales can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon on the Internet, it is played on the opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"There is also a desk with trained staff at these places, which advises interested parties when purchasing the Internet and also places the coupon on the map," said the speaker of the project Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, you can also play the electronic coupons on the opencard on self-service machines, which are installed in some underground vestibules.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, remind of ticket devaluers, passengers may have noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year it should be eighty," adds Opatrný.
Controlling the coupon instead of the driver
The operation of the vending machines, which will work from tomorrow, is easy.
All you have to do is insert the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon plays itself.
From tomorrow, the electronic coupons will apply not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which especially the inhabitants from communities of the region of central Bohemia reach the capital.
"In the trains that are part of Prague's integrated traffic, train attendants have readers that allow them to check the validity of coupons by time and by zone," explains Filip Drápal of the Ropid organisation, explaining ticket control. This organisation compiles the schedules for Prague's transport companies.
The suburban buses have card readers at the driver's ticket office.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the opencard must be placed in a marked position at the side of the checkout.
The driver controls the validity of the coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the issued coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information," says Drápal.
A passenger who does not drive suburban buses and no longer knows when the coupon expires can in turn go to the self-service machines where the coupons are played on the card.
Here the information about the validity of its documents is displayed on the display of the device.
