With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the U.S. President in 1945.
This can be seen, among other things, from a letter which has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian scientific library.
In the letter, the Germans of Krumau ask the American President not to allow the return of the "Sudetengaus" - which was taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," says a letter signed with the words "people to whom the fate of the Sudeten lies at their heart."
Since the connection to Czechoslovakia leads the Sudeten Germans - in the knowledge of the Czech national character - to suspect that they would expect brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take over the protection of the Bohemian Forest for the present and forever.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants of this area, you are a candidate for a state that is foreign to us, which is trying to suppress and eliminate minorities and has done nothing to contribute to the victory of the Allies," the letter says.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of revenge lusts of the "Czech oppressors".
If the U.S. President has doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it is sufficient for him to initiate a referendum in the Bohemian Forest Valley on whether the inhabitants wanted to become part of the U.S. or live under the protective rule of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naive in today's knowledge of post-war history, according to some contemporary witnesses, however, it draws a good picture of the Sudeten Germans' expectations at the time.
Even if the Bohemian Germans at least had to suspect that they would negotiate their deportation from the republic, only a few of them accepted such a possibility at all.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Others believed that they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
He was assigned to the Navy on the Baltic Sea during the war as a German Budweiser.
When he came into British captivity at the end of the war and was taken to a prisoner-of-war camp in Holstein, dozens more Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, the Czech would fit them," said Chalupa.
In his opinion, none of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected him to be expelled from the Republic on the basis of the Beneš decrees.
