Rats also have feelings
A rat or a cockroach flees in case of danger means that it also feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
Only how could they feel the same if they behave in a way similar to ours?
The Internet magazine " Edge" has been publishing contributions from famous scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else being able to prove this so far where we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, at least we can hope because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and raise questions of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter impenetrable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it turns itself in, flees, or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe in that, though.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its involvement in short-term memory and execution/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in man than in the rest of the primates and seems to be completely absent from other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since such a large part of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness does not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, however it may be, may differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness might look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor analysed on the basis of our own experience, because of the special hardware, then his research presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness, which should be more easily accessible scientifically.
One could examine the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their content, and this is exactly what is happening in studies of the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one shifts rather to the neural correlates of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: both may be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the emergence of visualization.
What is the result of the sensations?
I attribute it to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in one of its own activity conscious brain.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state we are in when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) proves memory.
In this way, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that distinguish primates and, in particular, humans.
Connected with linguistic nature, there are fine gradations of feeling, because with the help of words and grammar we can differentiate and categorize states in order to attribute them to others as well as ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations arise from more primitive activities in the body-feeling regions of the cortex and brain stem similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, concentrates more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed very much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in cross-generation sensations.
In theory, I cannot disagree with this, but I think it is unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans probably also feels this way in both cases: How, however, can rats and humans be verified to feel the same if they behave similarly?
A cockroach flees at risk whether she too feels fear?
In my eyes, mere behavioral resemblance cannot yet prove an equal experience.
The neural comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain strains, while cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove that for humans, how did you want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, perhaps even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and speech), I prefer to explore emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is being made at the neural level, provided that the same is being measured in rats and humans.
How I don't study language and consciousness in rats, or feelings, I don't know if they exist.
