`Sangre de mayo': Hero Book by Garci
Inspired by `Episodios Nacionales' by Benito Pérez Galdós, José Luis Carci in `Sangre de mayo' presents the revised version of the famous Spanish insurrection against the French. This is an admirable film in filmography, with about 15 million euros of investment for filming.
In this way, the Cineast has attempted to 'present a lot of personalities and social analysis', which he has always admired in the works of the famous novelist, Carci today explained at the presentation of the film with Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría at the beginning of a long list of actors.
`Sangre de mayo' with a film length of more than two and a half hours, is presented this Friday in cinemas and later shown on the telemadrid station as a four-hour miniseries.
José Luis Garci, a great fan of Galdós' literature, assures us that thanks to this film his 'childhood dream' came true. He owes this to Esperanza Aguirre, who commissioned him three years ago from the autonomous community of Madrid to make a memorial film for the second century celebration in Madrid on 2 November. Above all, because the story is based on 'Episodios Nacionales', he accepted the commission.
The total contribution of 15 million made for filming by the autonomous community of Madrid offers, as he added, the 'one-time possibility' with the help of decorations and corresponding clothing the image of 'confused Spain, which chose the false leader for the fight because the people had been left behind by the struggle for independence and under the rule of Ferdinand VII'.
However, the Cineast regrets that the financing could not be expected as with `Alatriste' or `Los fantasmas de Goya' (twice as high as with `Sangre de mayo'), so some scenes from the script with Horacio Valcárcel, with whom Garci worked almost his entire career, could not be shot.
For this reason, Garci, who was also film director in 'Volver a empezar', has participated through his usual way of working: he stood on stage with the actors with whom one first has to rehearse before one starts to shoot and for those who had not done casting he appeared 'demeaning' and respectful, 'a part of the profession of film director consists of providing help in theater and cinema to know what is happening in the cinema industry in which one works.'
Many actors he encounters in 'Sangre de mayo' must repeat in front of his camera, as in the case of Miguel Rellán, Carlos Larrañaga or Fernando Guillén Cuervo.
Garci, Oscar candidate in four nominations (of which he has won one), is of the opinion and assured that none of the three candidates representing Spain this year before the Academy of Hollywood represents a young generation of Spanish filmography. Neither `Sangre de mayo', nor `Siete mesas de billar francés' and, finally, not the selected film `Los girasoles ciegos'.
For this film, Garci does not expect any awards.
'In the beginning you think you're working for the progeny, later you realize that it's only for flourishing, and now you're happy when you've still produced a movie,' says Garci after more than 30 years of professional activity.
Isabel Bayón recalls the memory of the dancer from Seville Tórtola Valencia
A flamenco dancer from Seville adores a dancer who is also from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Catalane (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and her mother Andalucian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in the Triana district and when she was three years old, her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and expert in oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first fighters for the emancipation of the woman, such as Isadora Ducan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, vegetarian, and advocated the abolition of the corset, which restricted the free female movement.
Isabel Bayón was fascinated by the life of this woman, who left her mark on the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe in the period between the wars.
'I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested this role to me, which seemed impossible to me.'
'We're not trying to tell about her life, but to preserve her esprit,' said the flamenco dancer.
Your dance bases have helped me a lot in Flamenco.
'The Dance of the Butterfly' seemed to me like Guajira, for example, or 'The Dance of the Snake' like Tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I was told that my dancing was also in this aesthetic area,' she claims.
The production anticipates two extraordinary collaborations: Miguel Poveda, who will sing again for Isabel at one of her performances, as he did in 'La puerta abierta'; and with Flamenco master Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work with one of her ex-students.
`Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work, and I am very honored.'
The production also anticipates musical composition and the guitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, with the vocals of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; with the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with the actor Juanfra Júarez, he 'takes over the role of companion of the artists who were divas, to whom he falls in love again and again.'
This work also tells in a certain way about the life of this woman, who became known in places as far away as India, the United States or Russia, and also throughout Europe, although she usually lived in London.
'I wanted to call her back in memory, because I think she is one of the women who have an enormous influence on a certain epoch and whose works no one knows anymore and therefore appreciates her even less,' Bayón claims.
The performance takes place today at 20:30 at the Theatre Lope de Vega.
