Conversation - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to be happy because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
Above all, it has regained public confidence, which had been seriously shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
It is known that during the 1980s national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross blood donation service were contaminated with the HIV virus and hepatitis C virus.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, in February 1994 the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy, and to develop guidelines to prevent another catastrophe of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to submit his report, several provinces then set up a committee whose aim was to develop a new system for managing blood cans in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this task.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, who is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
`In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started her work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, remembers Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and through the work in this field during the following years, we have regained public confidence', she says, before proudly stressing that in early 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its foundation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting on the principle of caution.
At this time we witnessed the emergence of numerous cases of human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, told this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
'And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we relied on one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was transmitted through the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied has quite a sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which allow the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than one week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it, and one could not see this, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is in danger of getting HIV - infected blood.
'In other words, it means that you have to distribute 12 million canned blood before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cans each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs where HIV was transmitted via a blood can.
I think you can feel comfortable with it these days when you get or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore health," says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year has the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, just like the Westnil virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We need to monitor continuously,' continues Dr. Décary, before stressing that Hema-Quebec must provide adequate care in addition to a safe supply.
'The need is increasing because the population is aging.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which on average accounts for only 3% of Quebec's residents suitable for blood donation.
Every healthy person, who is 18 years of age or older and meets the eligibility criteria, can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because, for example, they are ill with AIDS or malaria, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from blood donation for one year.
`With these 3%, we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of the hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It's hard to convince people to donate blood, but especially to keep them and get them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour giving blood,' regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood preserves, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is used almost exclusively in case of severe fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed, and frozen before being intermediated at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec's only public umbilical cord blood bank.
The umbilical cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, contains blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to reduce more than a thousand annually.
'We should probably start making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year,' explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of umbilical cord blood removal as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced that they do not have access to it', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all of Quebec's hospitals.
