Many voters believe that they will find their salvation in a party that preaches virtue, law and order, but they do not see that this government has renounced what made our country's reputation and dignity.
The shame, Mr. Toews, lies in this renunciation, and nowhere else.
Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice-Director-General of the Barrick Gold Mine in Canada.
This confirms, and follows an Orwellian logic, that the world's largest gold mining company sought a libel lawsuit over six million against three authors and a small penniless publishing house, with the aim of opening a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially not in the case of libel lawsuits, but about the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to have a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposite opinions.
No matter how the trial proceeds, the authors and editors of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defenses and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactics in these unequal struggles are, moreover, often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual settlement that silences the other side and also deters anyone who dares to deal with the question again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things to public opinion.
In contrast to what is common in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates are usually held in Canada through the exchange of ideas and not through billets.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened a real debate through which newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent inspection teams could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes aside the petitions and letters to support the authors of Noir Canada with a hand move.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can at the same time ask for a 'public' debate, disregarding the opinions of this very public?
Apparently, this word in the vice-president's world includes only generous paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a very narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public, who supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada, does so mainly because it rejects the brutal attitude of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a gag suit (in the course of the 'public debate', Barrick Gold has just addressed a demand to the authors of Noir Canada in which they require them to stop using this term...).
Apart from Mr Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's lawsuit is a direct attack on freedom for academic research and truth-finding, which are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to quote credible sources and discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss topics that the rich companies of this world do not like, then who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long known how to deal with debates and disagreements and how to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, unlike what she pretends, she does not want a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit this kind of unjustified lawsuits.
Wall Street bailout - Democrats and Republicans get along
The Bush administration and senior congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached agreement yesterday on the most extensive economic recovery plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the plan over $700 billion, which is intended to stop the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months, still needs to be adopted by the two congressional chambers.
The main features are: better control by MEPs of the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to secure the repayment of public funds used, new injunctions to curb the number of houses pledged due to arrears, and the right to monitor the salaries paid to the executives of the companies supported.
The American finance secretary Henry Paulson, the president of the Nancy Pelosi Chamber of Deputies, and the Republican representative present at the negotiations, Senator Judd Gregg, announced yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, the good news, after a two-day negotiation marathon.
'We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective on the market,' said the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
'Everything happened to protect the real economy and the American people from the price crisis on Wall Street,' explained the Democrat.
'This is the basic point: if we don't, the trauma, chaos and unrest in the daily lives of Americans will be enormous,' explained Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had accelerated over the last two hours, for fear of the effect that a renewed failure would have had on the mood of investors.
The deadline that had been agreed was the market opening this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who took part in the negotiations only late, were more likely to be supporters of the agreement, but without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the fact that they had to be met in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on the addition of certain warrants for agreement, especially those intended to allow owners to keep their homes, and those relating to the salaries of executives of companies saved from the state.
'If you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain people, that is nothing to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary,' he said on American television stations.
When asked on another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied, 'I would like to know the details first, but I hope so.
`The guidelines I have read [show] that this is one thing that we all will have to digest, and with which we will be able to progress.
The option of doing nothing is simply unacceptable,' he said.
The 700 billion dollar plan is designed to use taxpayers' money
It comes 14 months after a crisis, triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble, which initially led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprime) before it expanded to further forms of more widespread bonds (PCAA), and eventually resulted in a freeze of financial strength and ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican MPs who made the first attempt to reach agreement last week fail.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain 'poisonous' assets of societies in distress should only be secured by the government and not be bought, it is believed to escape the impasse.
To round off the perspective for everyone in Congress, an injunction has also been added that if the government were to make losses with this program within five years, it could then levy new taxes in order to get back its invested capital.
The new plan provides for the payment of an initial sum of 250 billion, to which a further 100 billion can be added if the President considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion must be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In return for his assistance, Washington receives shares in the assisted companies that pay him dividends in the event of profits, and which it can sell again when the storm has passed.
The Federal Government will have the option of stopping the seizure procedures relating to the dwellings linked to the real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as setting deadlines for the repayment and severance payments paid to the executives of the companies concerned.
The developers of the plan would like the Chamber of Deputies to vote on him already today, and the Senate then on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get the green light.
In fact, there were further votes against this proposal yesterday, both from the Republicans and the Democrats.
'It is obvious that Washington does not understand us,' declared Republican Scott Garett, member of the Chamber of Finance Commission, to his constituents.
'Yes, we have a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists of asking taxpayers to pay.'
Democratic MP Brad Sherman, head of a group in Congress called 'the Caucus of Skeptics', presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
'Four hundred excellent economic professors, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us to tell us: we ask Congress not to be pressured, and to consider carefully what course to take,' he said yesterday.
At the same time, we in Europe were once again shown that this is a global crisis.
At an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the banking group Fortis for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US dollars).
Intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would refrain from buying up its competitor, who has been in great difficulty since losing EUR 2 billion (US$ 2.9 billion) in the crisis due to risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
'This is not lost money, declared yesterday the Dutch Minister of Finance Wouter Bos.
To compensate, we receive a right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what savers and households value now that uncertain times are about to come.'
During this time, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government was in the process of nationalizing another bank in distress by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all current loans from Bank Bradford and Bringley, of which over 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) are real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the UK bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be, after Northern Rock, the second bank the British government has had to nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
