What was produced in the invoice factory of Hammerg &amp; Co.?
On 8 October, the trial of Jáno's contract and his accomplices will begin.
In particular, the accused are accused of involvement in organised crime, grossly negligent damage and business fraud, and other criminal acts, including document falsification.
According to the prosecutor's office, the funds generated from the tenders were used for their own purposes, while the services provided were often accompanied by counterfeit invoices.
State funds and grants from the self-government - a total of HUF 65 million - are said to have been partly paid into the funds of the organisation Fiatal Baloldal, partly into the private funds of individual companies.
As the investigating authorities announced, fictitious invoices were submitted when the tender funds were collected and the clubs were not supposed to have fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the bills were faked.
The invoice blocks were bought at the market of Józsefváros, the round seals were made in Kiskunhalas.
The decision on which companies to issue the invoices was decided on that tour north of Lake Balaton, to which István Lados of Jáno's contract was sent.
In the course of this "exploratory tour" Lado was to find pensions and restaurants.
He demanded bills on consumptions so that he could later issue bills based on these templates for the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the self-government of Budapest.
These bills are said to have been largely manipulated by István Lados and his accomplice, András ḥri, the latter being responsible for the constitution of the reports according to our information.
One of the destinations of Lados' "exploratory tour" was a beer restaurant.
According to two invoices issued by Hammer and Co in 2003, the catering company is said to have hosted the ninety-strong group of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
But now the head of the company says that such a large group would not have fit into the restaurant at once.
Another bill issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, also showed serious form and content errors.
In a guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj, which has only three rooms and can accommodate no more than ten people at the same time, 130 guests are said to have stayed according to the bill.
The imagination of the falsifiers was obviously no longer limited when it came to the Pigal Kft., a catering company, in whose accounting documents of the customers Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá did not even appear, according to the prosecution.
As Managing Director Győző Farkas told hvg.hu, he immediately realized that these were fake documents when documents were submitted to him by the prosecutor during an interrogation.
"Our company name and tax number were misplaced on the stamp".
And further: Apart from formal errors, the fact that the company is said to have housed one hundred people was also wrong, after having a total of eleven rooms, which are impossible to accommodate so many people.
The restaurant had also been listed on the bill as catering, but the restaurant had not been operating for a long time.
The emphatic falsifiers have also failed to verify that the Budapest travel agency they are targeting offers only travel abroad, and so they have indicated Hungary travels on the cash payment account, which also contradicted the company's accounting practice.
As was known in the course of the investigation, they also cited VAT on invoices, although travel agency services relating to a country outside the EU are exempt from VAT.
The total amount of VAT was wrong on four invoices issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, as the company offsets only 15 percent VAT instead of 25. Moreover, the employees only issue machine invoices, but the forged documents were handwritten.
Another mistake that had been made by the "invoicers" was that in one case they had indicated "goods transport" as a service rendered, although this is not offered by the company specializing in investment advice, the prosecutor's office informed.
Further formal errors - wrong invoice format, wrong stamp - were due to the fact that the invoices issued to Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, as well as to XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont could be exposed as forgeries.
Also in the case of Ravenna Bt. and the sports camp Kunfehértó, whose managing directors affirmed never to have issued the invoices.
Another "mistake" has been made by the counterfeiters at the Hib Kft. from Nyíregyháza: This company was in disarray at the time (2001), when the group of the Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have eaten there - the mass administrator therefore stated that they had not issued the invoices themselves.
Consciously Fake
