The Psychology of Exceeding - or Why We Are Ready to Pay More
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bid.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even inflated prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was to play lottery while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured at auction losers, in which the opponent's overtaking plays an important role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-remuneration" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by the avoidance of an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, economists in the research group also conducted investigations to trace the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group were also promised $15 reward in case they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore only that the emphasis was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "against losing" group were ready for higher stakes than those in the control group or the "win" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
In fact, the behaviour observed at auctions has so far only been motivated by the joy of winning or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation ready" - said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Department of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should the doctor be consulted?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death in Hungary.
The number of people infected in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from one another.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. by contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (e.g. semen, vaginal secretion or saliva).
In any case, travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B, and there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are approximately two-three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine dark, and recovery can take up to two-three weeks.
Around 1 million people worldwide die every year from the far more severe diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten people infected is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most people who are infected do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen destroys the liver cells insidiously - in many cases the first symptoms show up after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular checks, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease occurs more frequently: those who underwent blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognised in good time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th is the World Day of Hepatitis, 2004 for the first time organized by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to increase awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their development and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
According to recent research, religious belief is a kind of "mean of pain" that is said to have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment: It was examined to what extent belief in God influences the feeling of pain of man, reports the British paper "Telegraph".
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
The results showed that the faithful were able to eliminate most of the pain.
By means of a brain scan technology, it could even be proven that Catholics could activate the part of their brain responsible for pain regulation.
The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university participate.
During the experiment, a sparkling device was attached to the left hand, which gave off the electric shocks.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand a painting of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame with the Hermeline".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary among the faithful would create a kind of religious trance, while they chose da Vinci's image because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt as reassuring.
The subjects each spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they were supposed to view either the religious, or the other painting.
Catholics reported that at the sight of the Mother of God they felt "in safety" as if they were "concerned" and they felt "peace and quiet".
While viewing the religious painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in mind.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the experiment, said that you could also create similar effects with other, strong-acting images with the atheists, you just had to find the corresponding photo.
"We need to find a picture that triggers very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father," the psychologist says.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practising the faith should change our personality, and it does so in many cases," says Wright.
After these excellent results, only the question remains, what effect a Madonna painting of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
You are what you share about yourself
On the occasion of their tenth birthday, Google can claim that it can be found in people's pockets just as it can be found above their heads in the sky: it knows where people have spent their holidays, which specialists they go to, and what moves them.
And that's still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of Google's managing directors.
Towards sceptics plagued by Orwell's horror visions, he says: These would just overlook the essentials of Web 2.0.
In an interview with the Financial Times recently, Schmidt said that Google's main objective was to collect even more personal data about users and thus to get closer to the company's original objective, according to which it wanted to "order all information in this world."
Schmidt stated that Google is still only at the beginning of collecting information after ten years of world-changing work.
Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said: he wished Google would be able to answer questions like "What should I do tomorrow?" or "Which job really suits me?", but software programs are not yet able to do so, as they do not know enough about the users.
Not all Internet users are aware that in the course of their Internet searches the search terms would be registered, as well as the IP addresses from which they were searched and the pages visited.
For example, the "Personalized Search" introduced two years ago allows visitors to save their own search history and later use it so that the hits can be generated much more precisely later, and the so-called "recommendations" are also based on the same logic with which the system recommends tailor-made products and services based on previous preferences.
However, users wonder what happens in the event of data abuse - "When you look at what I do" - some are worried about the Google data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is more the company's represented, potential power that is terrifying, and less the feeling of guilt or fear of punishment, the pursuit of freedom, or the revolt against power that many internet users encounter with rejection.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored, but also passed on to third parties in the event of an event, and in these cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
A prime example of this was the recent action against paedophilia in Brazil, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information collected by the community site called "Orkut" and also made it possible to identify the pedophilia.
However, users concerned with personal rights were able to breathe a sigh of relief in May when Google, together with the civil rights organization EFF, successfully brought the FBI to justice: thus, Google cannot be forced to release information to the FBI on a secret request with any point of the constitution in the future.
(However, the Federal Government has successfully obtained the publication of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms with reference to the Youth Protection Act adopted years ago, but the list of individual users, or their web and search terms list, has been withheld retroactively for two months.)
So Google's image remains controversial: those who reluctantly release their personal data because they fear the loss of their private and private sphere by using Google services, scourge the company with the outrage due to the conservative companies.
However, the American "geek culture", which is present in many countries and unites enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, sees the next generation of "cool entrepreneurs" in them, unlike Microsoft, which is market leader thanks to Windows, even if both struggle for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that, unlike Microsoft, Google does not require identification codes for its users and provides its services free of charge, so that an open, constantly updated source code and program package seems to be far more attractive, youthful and cooler than the official practices of the software giant.
On the other hand, the geeks see through the problematic relationship of personal rights and the Internet razor-sharp - a relationship that has come to the fore especially in recent years thanks to the term "Web 2.0".
The "Web 2.0" is about nothing but collaboration, i.e. the users intentionally leave traces and use the available communication channels, and even if the dimensions are individually different, the main thing remains the same, namely to show itself publicly.
An average youth can simultaneously manage his profile on several community portals - from Facebook via Xanga, can connect it through other services, such as Twitter, or music services such as last.fm, and can eventually integrate all of this into a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. In addition, they can run blogs that automatically display the latest photo galleries that are geosted on Flickr or Picasa.
And a number of other examples prove: When looking at the party photos of the past night, the girlfriend soon finds out who her unfaithful friend has been enjoying himself with, or the employee is fired because in his blog he is only too honest about his anger about the management of the company - one thing is for sure: The term "privacy" has now been completely reinterpreted.
Those who lead an online life are what they reveal to themselves - this is how one could formulate the basic idea behind the behavior of today's youth.
And those who try to keep something secret, or even circumvent Google's monopoly, are welcome to do so - such as Scroogle, a tool that accesses Google's search engine, but intentionally leaves no traces.
Not a few people deliberately do not register on community sites so that they are not findable, but also Google's online applications, such as text processing and graphical tools and RSS feeds, can be handled with alternative versions that are not linked to huge server parks and therefore do not generate the best possible profile from the user.
Public opinion, however, anxiously waits for Google to show its true face.
With its current value of USD 156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM (USD 140 billion), Intel (USD 124 billion) or Coca-Cola (USD 110 billion), AdWords/AdSense's advertising space is threatening advertising agencies' revenues, and the fast-paced services are causing worry not only to Microsoft but also to other software developers.
Critical observers, however, also find the disturbing counterpoles: for example, the corporate management rejected a protest from the employees completely after the company's kindergarten fees were doubled, and management also thought that the staff's multiple meals were too expensive. However, all this seems to be mildly opposed to Google even falling to the knees before the Chinese government in 2006 and agreeing with an agreement that all the regime-critical hits, or those that violate the good taste, would be filtered out.
The internal regulation of the group is that no new service is advertised in advance, but only if it is already available. Nevertheless, the events of the coming months and years could again change a lot: While some believe that Google's book and magazine scan or archiving project now assumes dimensions that the company would soon have to deal with the Supreme Court, others are rather concerned about the "Health" system, which enables the creation of a complete health profile based on findings, doctors and problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database already provides the next generation of sci-fi authors with the material - such as "Scroogled", the famous novel by Cory Doctorow describes in the best Orwellian manner a future in which a human being becomes scaryly approachable thanks to Google-related data.
