Intelligent car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new accident prevention technologies if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
CEATEC in Japan presented an amazing project that inspired the Nissan engineers of bumblebees in the creation of new systems to prevent accidents.
In cooperation with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system controlled by car robots, a mini car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private sector", which is very similar to our own "protective shield", Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, said at the exhibition.
The compound eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a visual field of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of seconds, and the car robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tires around the appropriate angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this manoeuvre takes place purely instinctively.
"If it wasn't, the car robot couldn't react fast enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the Car Robot Project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of bees when they avoid other bees.
And this has to take place in a fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to bees, dodging cannot take place up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only towards the maneuverability of the tires.
While there are endless possibilities for the bees here to avoid other bees, the researchers in the car robot were only able to use the rotational motion, or acceleration and deceleration.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer service life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only has to process a few inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It does not have to save them, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction based on previous maneuvers, so that it constantly takes up only a handful of KB memory.
There's no need for gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan believes will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately directing the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the destination.
