Sales prices in the country were only slightly higher than in the previous month, i.e. by 0.1 percent.
Sales prices in the manufacturing industry also rose only a little - 0.1 percent - since July.
The largest price increase in August 2008 was for leather goods (2.8 percent) - mainly for bags and belts - here the increase was 4.6 percent, for shoes prices were up 2.5 percent.
Higher prices for plastics and chemical raw materials significantly increased the prices for chemicals and productions (1.6 percent).
A price decline was recorded in crude oil processing (1.4 percent), in electrical and technical equipment (0.9 percent), and in wood processing (0.1 percent).
Prices in paper production, publishing and printing remained unchanged.
In other branches of the manufacturing industry, a price increase of between 0.2 and 0.9 percent was recorded.
