"The vast majority of Roma youths do not have middle school education, and due to poor primary education, only a small part of them can achieve higher education".
Járóka also stressed that education was a fundamental human right, which had a key role to play in asserting other human rights.
Investing in early education for Roma children could strengthen the economy of the EU Member States.
In the view of the honourable Members, it is important that these contexts should be as broad as possible - Roma and non-Roma - aware of them.
The sooner a Roma student starts school, the more his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market increase, and through income and VAT they contribute to national spending.
"As EU citizens, the Roma must be guaranteed the right to high-quality education - poor and segregated education must be stopped," said Lívia Járóka.
As the honourable Member said, a common, target- and action-oriented approach by the European Union is necessary in order to speed up the de-segregation process in the education sector, and to this end, proper compliance with existing and planned anti-discrimination directives is essential.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment and give Roma children the democratic means to contribute to the future of Europe as a fully entitled citizen," Járóka said.
Since last year's Congress in Berlin, the summit has been held annually with the aim of creating a unique forum for the advancement of the objectives of equal opportunities and freedom of discrimination at both European and national level, in the sense of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities".
