Napolitano: "Prevention of accidents at work is crucial"
Every day, 2500 accidents occur in Italy, three people die and 27 remain for life.
For the year 2007, data from the Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul Lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were about 1200.
These figures demonstrate the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) in all the provinces of Italy will celebrate the 58th National Day for the Victims of Accidents at Work in order to draw the attention of social institutions and media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention in the workplace is," confirms the President of the Republic of Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of the Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del Lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention at the workplace, to the protection of injured workers, to aid the families of the victims and to raising public opinion".
"An outraged "basta" has risen to this; understandable in tragedies that, measured by their magnitude, cause some vortex in the media and public sympathy. However, everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events that can even repeat themselves in their own dynamics".
Napolitano does not hide that "there is definitely also a resource problem: it must be invested decisively in education and information."
The numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness of the educational context are of particular importance for young people who feed the world of work.
It is our duty to pay attention to this phenomenon and not to distract it from its social seriousness. It is necessary to enforce and improve a legislative standard.
For his part, the President of Chamber Gianfranco Fini stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency, which insults the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards firm rules that aim to put an end to the problem".
"The data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight improvement, but this does not exclude the fact that the number of work-related deaths is far too high," stresses President of Anmil, Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this "positive tendency" to mean less attention, which is exactly what causes the tragedy in the end."
"How do you think that you are doing far too little to counter the phenomenon of accidents. You can fight against it through various actions.
