"Another effort is needed - he adds - in terms of communication and awareness-raising of public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that represents a social emergency is in demand".
Mercandelli also referred to "the progressive deterioration of protection for the victims of work accidents" and denounced the "abolition of the social system against which we are fighting in recent years".
"The aim is therefore to give the employee a guarantee on insurance so that the fate of the victim of an accident at work does not depend on voluntary or random donations that are currently decided by a legislator".
Mp3 player on charge: danger of hearing damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as Mp3 players, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
This is reported by the European Commission, which cites the opinion of the Csrseri (scientific committee on current and recently identified health risks) in a report published today in Brussels.
"The report – according to one note – makes it clear that 5-10% of those who listen to loud music with portable music equipment for at least five years a week for more than one hour a day risk permanent loss of their hearing".
"I am worried that such a large number of young people, who usually put portable music devices and mobile phones at a high volume, will irretrievably damage their hearing without knowing it," says Meglena Kuneva.
"The scientific findings – as it is said on the part of the Eu – show a clear risk that pushes too fast action.
What really matters is to raise consumer awareness and make this information common.
In the light of these scientific findings, we need to re-examine existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology".
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music equipment among young people.
"Scientists - as the EU Communication concludes - confirm that there is a legitimate concern and that the European Commission, together with the other EU members and stakeholders, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise coming from portable music equipment and similar equipment".
There is already a European standard which limits the level of noise from portable music equipment to 100 dB, and concerns about the damage that could result from too much noise.
This damage can be very limited by resorting to solutions such as reducing volume and length of noise exposure.
In its report, the Scientific Committee of the Eu points out that when users of portable music devices hear loud (less than 89 decibels) music only five hours a week, so that the legal limits that apply to the maximum noise level at the workplace are already exceeded.
Those who exceed this limit risk the complete loss of hearing within five years.
This represents 5-10% of users of such devices, the number of which can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the Eu.
