The elite is in danger
The phenomenon had already emerged a few days ago when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the White House's $700 billion savings package: a large part of Americans were and is more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This confirms yesterday's issue of The New York Times, which reports on how the crisis in progress divides the Republican party, which is increasingly splitting into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored state institutions and business community, and those neoconservatives hostile to "them in Washington" and the financial world, and, above all, winning voters in the south and the center of states.
This part of the party owes its rise above all to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
However, this example, just mentioned, is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake is or is already about to bring about: not only in the United States, but also throughout the West, and perhaps beyond that, will they be affected by it.
Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long-afraid events that are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the new discovery, the unheard-of renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis is a decline in banking and financial institutions, which have close links with foreign countries and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the wealth of households living in a single state.
This is a direct political problem for governments: how to behave towards the families concerned, which are also an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis thus appears economically global, whereas politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have gone out of hand and lost its right to speak: the clear proof of this has been given by the EU, which, due to its division into different national and international conflicts, cannot find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now anticipates the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and above all distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became increasingly serious, only the US is in the economic situation to save itself without foreign help.
In addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus, two conditions that cannot be overvalued – under certain circumstances – which no international organisation or market will otherwise be able to rely on in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance which recently has been associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, when we were so convinced that we had long since entered a networked empire, a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, of intangibles, it is precisely now that we must suddenly see how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can certainly all be transported from one place to another in the world, but they are still connected to a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such a territory is in favor of another who lives in a cropless, waterless or oil-free area.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a short insert.
Who territory, who government, who says politics, thus also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leaderships, that is, the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation over the existing leaderships, especially those of economics, which have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
In addition, there is a deeper and, in a sense, still disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, an intolerance, an image of inefficiency, a sense of remoteness, all of which is directed at an entire class of Western managers.
It seems to be the conviction among large parts of the population that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content is more and more alien and traditional to the majority.
The demand for leadership is thus fueling a branched but powerful movement of the disempowerment of the leading class and the traditional political establishment. This manifests itself in unforeseen "revolts" of voters and in the sudden reversal of the collective state of mind of recent times: starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, about the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, towards the rebellion of American MPs against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy also plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, have more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value regarding what is going on today in the lower social strata of the West and is being intensified and driven by the financial crisis to over-dimensionality.
In view of all this, it would simply be exaggerated to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The super glue that lets go up on walls
Defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and climb up walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which seems to have almost reached the target.
With an adhesive applied on an area of only 2.5 sqcm, the researchers succeeded in fixing a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
The STUDIO – an American journal has published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
