"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged into a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang from the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists have been inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered by microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
The tests carried out with various materials, such as glass Teflon and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the reptile's feet' holding ability and, at the same time, "is easily removed from the wall," says Liming Dai, researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
"This material could be used as a transitory adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe so, but the researchers think of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other areas of application could fall within the space sector.
So for the moment the superheroes still have to wait.
THE OTHER TYPE OF RESEARCH – the University of Berkeley, California, is also dedicated to a new type of glue.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, California scientists present a microfibre adhesive that, like hair, cleans itself from the dust by moving on a surface and thus always retains perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Be careful of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These beverages, which are consumed mainly in the summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, can cause serious health damage if they are taken at the same time with certain vital medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points to the risk of both packaged and fresh fruit juices in connection with medication intake. During the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again sounded the alarm: it is enough to have a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital drugs to the extent that they are practically eliminated and thus endanger the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, up to toxic levels.
MEDICALS IN DRIVER – In a report two years ago, the same agency had warned doctors and patients of the dangers of this mix and stressed the need to take care of what is being drunk in connection with drugs such as diazepan or metadon.
It's NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT – According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active substances inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Therefore, the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the Università Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually forwarded immediately to the various international manufacturers, who are thus free to change consumer information.
It is therefore recommended to read the package leaflet at all times and, if there is still some ambiguity, to ask a pharmacist or a doctor," the Ansa agency's expert stresses.
