Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package appears
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the Open Source software, as a free replacement for Microsoft's Office, is gaining an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers, which is monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is now presenting itself to the public with some novelties: in addition to a revised and now Spartan designed initial menu, a completely guaranteed compatibility with Apple's operating system Mac OS x has finally been achieved, as well as the support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.e. the latest standard ISO version.
In addition, the compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice, has been taken into account.
Also interesting are some new features, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes sending via email easier. This also includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphics editing modules and at the same time preserve the original appearance of the page.
So you can now generate "hybride" PDF files, which expand the typical graphics of Adobe format by the elements of a table and a text processing system.
The collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be edited several hands by different users, thus avoiding conflicts in the case of changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a question in order to guarantee a better correction procedure.
Some companies are currently releasing various OpenOffice features on the Internet (on the cloud), while the final result is to be made public in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download on the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. Thus it follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
Except for Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request you can send the installation CD to your home or office.
However, if the cost-free nature of the programme can be an incentive for the dissemination of the programme in private households, it is also particularly in the area of business where OpenOffice could succeed: after all, various public administration and schools have already moved to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of training, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word corresponding text creation program; Calc, the table program aimed at pushing Excel; Impress, for creating presentations such as with PowerPoint; Dbase for operating databases instead of the more known access; and most recently Draw, a graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads – a target that can be easily exceeded with already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
