Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema – the cities close their historic cinema halls
The historical cinemas close due to the favored multiplexkinos.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture by director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening at the moment in the major urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of the exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, means in the long run death for the one-room cinema in the centre. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the features of a cultural crime.
It is mostly historical places full of memories, "it is like losing a friend with whom one has travelled a piece of street full of emotions", according to the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", which 20 years ago earned him the Oscar and the great prize of Cannes. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably lost forever.
The figures supplied by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas has had to close; most of these mines paid for cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This proves that the main culprits are the multiplexkinos, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: at 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 are in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
"Business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, President of Anec, "although it is useful that new structures also emerge, the first priority is the preservation of the already existing one, because if a hall closes in the city, not all its regular customers are willing to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here remains the lack of budget for the funds of the trade association external eight: the debt burden recorded by the state amounts to about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be necessary".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city to have decided to protect the old cinemas by an agreement between the municipality and the Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to protect and support the traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the planned measures are also tax breaks for cinema operators, as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be allowed to travel to the traffic-limited areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
"It is a good initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also develop new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to do something against the superpower of the multiplex halls, because after all, the audience of today is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closing of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the thought for 10 years.
For 25 years I have been living in Rome; when I pass by the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside to avoid seeing the dusty posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
