When the energy comes out of the waves, the big ones suddenly start running
It is a non-depleting source of money that covers over 70% of the planet's surface and only now do the world's major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now all looking at, and are also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of generating energy from ocean movements has been under consideration and studied for 70 years; not by chance, these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil fell around 1980, the idea of ocean energy was gassed, but now environmental organizations and increased oil prices are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy needs could be met by the energies generated by ocean waves.
This would be twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides are added.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this message was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy sector are now relying on marine energy generation.
"Chevron investigates these technologies" – according to the spokesman of a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal – and weighs the opportunity to work with us."
This is about obtaining a permit from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign that should not be underestimated, especially given that, especially in Alaska, oil continues to be mined by the US and President Bush recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; even if the details are not known, observers are talking about an increasing interest.
Even better technologies.
Experts are talking about an emerging technology, not least because the last doubts have not yet been clarified by environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small scale and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a far greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned plants of this type, which are only waiting for state approval. Part of the energy gained could also be used for military facilities.
However, Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and a park latz using submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feeds the generator through the resulting rotary motion.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Production Research, a particular interest currently deserves the potential that is in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is especially tidal energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
